WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:10.560
Welcome to the RStudio Enterprise Community Meetup. I'm Rachel Dempsey. I'm calling in from

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:16.879
Boston today. For today's meetup, we'll learn how the team at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:23.440
is translating facts into insights and learn more about a new package for generating useful

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:29.040
talking points. But with that, thank you all again so much for joining us. I'd love to turn

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:35.360
it over to our speaker for today, Jake Riley. Jake is a data analyst at the Children's Hospital

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:41.040
of Philadelphia and the author of several R packages related to data visualization and

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:46.560
automated exploratory analysis. I'll stop my share here and turn it over to you, Jake.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:53.119
So hi, everyone. It's cool to see such big people from all over the world joining the talk today.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:58.080
So yeah, my name is Jake Riley. I'm a data analyst at CHOP. It's the Children's Hospital of

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:03.680
Philadelphia. I love doing data visualization and geospatial analysis. I've also built a couple of

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:09.120
R packages. One is called Simple Colors. That was my first package, which is just nice, simple,

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:15.760
nicely named colors. I'll share a link at the end to that vignette. One around just like working

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:19.120
with Shiny dashboards and then Headliner, which is the one we're going to talk about today.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:26.480
So when I think about building dashboards, I think there's kind of a spectrum of kind of how

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:30.559
the data can be presented. You could have a dashboard that's really more focused on facts,

00:01:30.559 --> 00:01:35.440
like the one on the left, versus one that's more focused on insights. So although these two

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:39.440
examples have the same underlying data, I think they have a really different user experience.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:45.040
The one on the left is really just totals, percentages, and I would say it's really

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:50.959
presenting facts, whereas the one on the right is sharing more context. So that number of 989

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:56.080
total applicants, what does it mean? Is it good? Is it bad? Is it high? Is it low? Is it expected?

00:01:57.519 --> 00:02:00.480
On the one on the right, there's a little more context here. So it's saying there's a 10%

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.800
decrease in candidates hired. And then it's telling more, there's a 20% increase in total

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.440
applicants. And if that were to continue, this will decrease the revenue by 8%.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:13.279
So the one on the left, I think, is a little easier out of the box,

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:18.240
but because it doesn't really provide that context, I think there's a risk of lower adoption.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:23.520
The one on the right, I think, has more context. I find it to be more meaningful, but I think it's

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:27.759
much harder to produce. And for that reason, I think it has a high risk of technical debt.

00:02:28.399 --> 00:02:33.600
Technical debt isn't a term you've heard of before. If I had to pick this up in six months,

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.240
or if I had to hand it off to somebody, how much time and energy is going to be used just trying to

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:44.080
catch up to speed or to make any modifications to it? So yeah, I think the one on the right is

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:49.919
really interesting, but I think it's really hard to accomplish. So if we look at an example of this

00:02:49.919 --> 00:02:55.839
plot, so I looked at, there's a package called CRANlogs, and you can say how often a package has

00:02:55.839 --> 00:03:00.800
been downloaded from CRAN. So I just looked at the tidyverse, and in particular, I picked the ggplot2

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:06.960
package and just plotted the number of downloads by month. So if we were to make a title for this

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:11.119
chart, there's a couple of different titles we might pick. We could say something like ggplot2

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:16.559
downloads by month. It's straightforward, but it's also kind of static. So it's the same title

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:23.119
every time we look at it. It's not really providing that context or that insight I was

00:03:23.119 --> 00:03:29.759
talking about. And because of that, because it's static and that title always works, it's a

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:34.240
relatively low list. Maybe it's dynamic, like you can pick what package we're looking at on

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:37.839
our dashboard, and all it's going to update is that we're looking at ggplot2, we're looking at

00:03:37.839 --> 00:03:45.360
gpli. The next one we could say is something like ggplot2 monthly downloads changed from 1.5 million,

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:50.320
and this is looking by year, so this is all 2020 versus all 2021. So we could say it changed from

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:56.000
1.5 million to 2.1 million. So that's going to be a little more dynamic. I would say the insights

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:03.039
are better, but still not, I don't quite have a lot of context. And it involves a little more

00:04:03.039 --> 00:04:07.679
lift, so I have to now kind of create some aggregations upstream to figure out what the

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:12.720
totals are by year, and then feed that into the title. What I think is a more interesting title

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:19.040
is something like ggplot2 monthly downloads increased by 44%, so 2.1 million versus a

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:25.040
prior value of 1.5 million. I would say that's a very dynamic title. I think it provides more

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:30.559
context and I think has some good insight, but it's a much heavier lift. So that phrase of

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:35.440
increased versus decreased, I think just gets tricky, and so I work on a team of a lot of,

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:42.160
we have a very large team of R users with all levels of experience. So someone might be able

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:47.839
to produce a sentence like that with a relatively short amount of code, and someone might write it

00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:52.079
in like several hundred lines of code, depending on kind of how they are trying to deal with the

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:59.200
grammar and syntax. And so for that reason, I like that title, but I just thought it had this like

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:05.839
risk of really producing a lot of technical debt or being hard to maintain and

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:12.320
edit over time. So headliner, that's this package I built to kind of help write those dynamic

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:19.119
sentences. So right out of the box, the main function is headline. So we just pass headline

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:25.200
two values. We say like compare x to y. So here I'm comparing the value of 32 to the value of 24.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:31.519
Just by default, it's going to spit out increase of 8, 32 versus 24. If I reverse those numbers,

00:05:31.519 --> 00:05:35.920
I'm saying tell me about 24 in comparison to 32, that number is lower. So it's going to just out

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:41.679
of the box say it's a decrease of 8. So what's going on with the hood is that headline is,

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:47.679
or headliner, and then this particular function headline is using the glue package. And so what

00:05:47.679 --> 00:05:53.200
I'm able to do is kind of string together different talking points to create these phrases.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.519
So under the hood of the headline function is this function called compare values. So when I

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:05.359
give compare values to numbers, it's going to spit out a list object with all these different like

00:06:05.359 --> 00:06:10.480
what I call talking points. So it's going to say the original y value is 24, the original x value

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:16.079
is 24, the y value is 32, the delta as an absolute value is 8. So I want to say increase of 8,

00:06:16.079 --> 00:06:21.040
decrease of 8. So even if the value is negative, I'm always going to display it as the positive.

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:26.079
So delta is going to be that absolute value. Delta p is the percentage difference. So it's

00:06:26.079 --> 00:06:34.880
a 25% difference. And I've timed that by 100 so that it's not a fraction. But then I also have

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:42.880
some phrases where I'm appending an article like a or an to the value. So an 8 verse 825. And then

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:48.640
I also have the raw delta value, the raw delta percentage. I have articles for both of those.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:54.640
And then I've also brought back the sign. So negative 1, positive 1 or 0 if there's no change.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:07:02.000
And that can be really useful in this package if you want to like color a value box on a Shiny app

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.679
based on if the value went up or down, you could use the sign to kind of control the color.

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:10.480
And then there's just like the shorthand of a rich values, which is going to say like 20

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:18.160
x verse y. And then there's a trend. There's this trend value, which in this case is bringing back

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:23.519
the decrease. So with those talking points, you can use glue to like string them together by

00:07:23.519 --> 00:07:28.720
putting them in curly braces. So I can say curly brace trend of curly brace delta,

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:35.040
parentheses, and then curly brace original values. So when headline reads that string,

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:39.440
it's going to put together this increase of 8 with this comparison, decrease of 8.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:46.480
So a little bit about glue. So what glue does is it embeds R's expressions in curly braces

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:52.640
and then combines them together to create a longer string. So an example of using glue would

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:59.760
be to say my age is 37, which it is. And then with glue, I can say I am and then in curly brace,

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:05.760
say my age, and then it will like find my age in the environment and then bring that back in this.

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:10.000
It's kind of like paste on steroids. You don't have to like kind of keep separating with commas

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.559
and quotes. You can just kind of like string it all together using the curly braces to plug in

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:20.959
your variables. And I think it's a very, very good package. So we could like try to write these

00:08:20.959 --> 00:08:27.040
headlines using just glue. So we could say, so you can create temporary objects as you call glue as

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:32.719
well. So I can say, I'm going to set up X is 24, Y is 32. And then in the curly braces, I can give

00:08:32.719 --> 00:08:39.679
it an expression to evaluate. And so this will kind of create that percentage difference. And

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:43.840
then I can say like X versus Y. So I can write a sentence that's like pretty similar to what

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.359
headlines spitting out, but headliner just simplifies those steps. So I can just say,

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:53.919
if I want to write the same type of sentence, I can just say Delta P percent, and then I can

00:08:53.919 --> 00:08:58.159
call trend. So this is lower. So it's going to be a decrease. And then that original value

00:08:58.159 --> 00:09:02.239
shorthand is going to bring back that, like what the before and after values are.

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:07.359
So some examples of like putting these together in different combinations.

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:12.320
So you can pass it a vector. So I passed it 8 through 12 and 12 through 8. So I have positive,

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:18.559
negative, and also an example of no change. So when I pass that to the headline function,

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:25.679
and I give it this string to evaluate, it's going to write there was a 33% decrease versus

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:31.440
an 18% decrease. If there's no, there's some control, you can like tell it what to write

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:37.039
if there's no difference at all. By default, it says there was no difference. But you can

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:42.960
specify what you want that to say. And then when the numbers were higher,

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:50.320
then it's saying a 22% increase, a 50% increase. So increase and decrease are the default values

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:55.200
for trend. So because they both end in an E, we can just add a D to the end. So if I just say

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:01.200
trend in the curly braces and just add a D, I'm going to get decreased, increased. And then again,

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:09.280
I'm using that delta P value to say by 20%. Or I could say decreased by 2, and then show like

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:15.520
the raw delta P, so negative 20%. Or I could write a sentence like, you know, the difference,

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:23.039
and then the curly braces and bring back the raw value sets like negative 2. So 8 from 10 is 2 less.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:30.239
So difference is negative 2. And then I'm writing a phrase like today equals the original x value,

00:10:30.239 --> 00:10:34.159
the prior is the original y value. And so it kind of creates this whole sentence for me,

00:10:34.719 --> 00:10:40.000
I think, relatively easily. So there's a lot of perks of using glue under the hood.

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:50.239
So as I mentioned earlier, you can make objects as you are calling the function. So if I said A

00:10:50.239 --> 00:10:54.799
is 1 and B is 2, I could write a sentence calling A and B, and then inside the curly braces,

00:10:54.799 --> 00:10:59.119
add them together. You can do other stuff because headlines using that under the hood,

00:10:59.119 --> 00:11:03.440
you can actually use a lot of the same tricks. So maybe I want to capitalize the first letter,

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:07.119
I could just create a little function. I mean, I could call this whole function,

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:10.239
which is from the stringer package, which is string to sentence that's going to capitalize

00:11:10.239 --> 00:11:15.679
the first letter. But just for shorthand, I'm just going to write cap equals, call that function.

00:11:15.679 --> 00:11:20.559
And then inside the curly braces here for the trend argument, which is going to be that decrease,

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:26.960
I can say capitalize that, add a D to the end. So now we have decreased by delta P,

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:33.440
percentage. And then I want to say as of today. And then today, I am just formatting today's date.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:39.919
And this is like a little shortcut to build out a date as like month, day, year. So yeah,

00:11:39.919 --> 00:11:46.239
so you can build objects inside as you call it, and then string those together as well.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.080
You can also concatenate them just using the plus operator. So I could say, yeah,

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:59.359
decrease of one, semicolon, increase of three. You can string them together like that.

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:06.080
And then there's a lot of control on how this stuff comes back. So by default, it's going to

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:11.760
say increase and decrease. But there's a trend phrases argument that headline takes. And you can

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:21.039
use this trend terms function to specify if the value, if x is higher than y, display. In this

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:24.960
case, I want it to display higher. If it's less, then I want it to display lower. So then when I

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:32.159
call this headline of trend by delta, I get lower by two. You can also pass it a named list. So here

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:38.320
in trend phrases, I'm passing a list of higher, which is going to be higher versus lower,

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:42.640
and then more, which is going to be more and less. So then when I string this together,

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:48.000
I can call that higher object that got created and say higher by this percentage.

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:54.640
And then I want to say two more. So the more is getting called from the trend phrase,

00:12:54.640 --> 00:13:01.039
and the higher is getting called from this one up here. So I've tried to make it pretty robust

00:13:01.039 --> 00:13:05.520
so that you can write a lot of different types of sentences. And then there's a similar rule for,

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:10.479
there's a similar method to deal with plurality. So if I want to say something like, we hired

00:13:10.479 --> 00:13:18.799
one person, first we hired two people, I can create this people and an object called people

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:23.679
and these employees, which it's going to look at the difference between the two values and say,

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:30.559
if the value is one, then bring back person, otherwise bring back people. So in the end,

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:35.359
I'm able to make phrases like we hired one new person, this employee will start Monday, June 20,

00:13:35.359 --> 00:13:42.559
or we hired two new people, these employees will start Monday, June 20. So yeah, we've got

00:13:42.559 --> 00:13:48.719
our X and Y values, these plural phrases, I'm using headline using the methods I described,

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:52.159
and then I'm creating an object called next Monday, where I'm just figuring out what the

00:13:52.159 --> 00:13:57.280
next Monday is and formatting it nicely. And then they just all get together and I get these nice

00:13:57.919 --> 00:14:02.880
dynamic phrases. There's also some helpers for dealing with data frames.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:11.200
I created one helper that's just called add date columns. And there's a built-in function

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:18.159
called demo data, which is just going to build a little data set with some groups and

00:14:19.119 --> 00:14:22.320
columns to aggregate on, but there's also a date column. So it's really just these first

00:14:23.679 --> 00:14:30.960
five columns here. So that's going to come from demo data, but then I can use add date columns.

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:34.799
And what that's going to do is it's going, you tell it what columns to look at. So add date

00:14:34.799 --> 00:14:40.559
columns is going to look at this demo data set, and then look at the date column and then figure

00:14:40.559 --> 00:14:45.840
out how far away that value is from today. You can tell it what date to reference, but by default,

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:49.760
it's going to count from today. So it's going to say, this is one day ago, this is one week ago,

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:56.479
sorry, I ran this yesterday. So it was zero days, zero weeks, zero months. But if I pick an earlier

00:14:56.479 --> 00:15:01.119
date, like from February, it's 120 days ago, it's 18 weeks ago, it's four months ago, one quarter

00:15:01.119 --> 00:15:08.000
ago, same calendar year, same fiscal year. And so by using this helper function of this add date

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:14.479
columns, I can then use this compare conditions function that is in headliner to say, compare when

00:15:14.479 --> 00:15:19.200
month is zero. So when it's the current month versus when month equals negative 12. So it's

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:25.359
going to compare the sales for this month versus 12 months ago. And it's really using the across

00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:32.479
function. So it's like filtering on a condition within the data set, and then using across to

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:39.359
aggregate it. So you can tell it to like aggregate, like using means and standard deviations to sum

00:15:39.359 --> 00:15:44.880
them to count the number of values. There's a lot of different ways you can aggregate the data,

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:50.400
but by default, it's going to grab the mean. So I just created this year over year object,

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:54.799
and it's going to spit back using compare conditions, it's going to return a data frame

00:15:55.440 --> 00:16:03.359
with the, it's going to say mean sales of x and mean sales of y. So with that data frame,

00:16:03.359 --> 00:16:08.719
I can then pass it to a function to create a headline. It's currently called headline list,

00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:14.159
I'm probably going to rename that at some point. But if I give it a data frame with one row,

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:19.440
it will know to return a headline from that because it's going to return a string. So if I

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:23.520
give it that year over year data frame that I just showed, pass it the headline list, it's going to

00:16:23.520 --> 00:16:31.359
write for us a decrease of 601 verse 107. If you have many rows, which this is a use case I use

00:16:31.359 --> 00:16:36.960
quite often, I want to create a headline for every row in the data set. You can use add headline

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:42.960
column. So there's a built in data set for headliner called Pixar films. And from here,

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:47.200
I'm just going to select the name of the film, it's Rotten Tomatoes score, and it's Metacritic

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:52.479
score. And I just want to compare like, which ones is the Rotten Tomatoes score higher than the

00:16:52.479 --> 00:16:58.719
Metacritic score? So by how much? So I can use add headline column. And this time, when I call

00:16:58.719 --> 00:17:05.760
x and y, those are going to be names of columns in my data set. So I'm going to compare Rotten

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:11.040
Tomatoes to Metacritic, and then I'm going to write a headline. So when I write the headline,

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:14.719
this time, I have not only the talking points that I described earlier, but I can also reference

00:17:14.719 --> 00:17:19.920
columns in my data. So I can say, film, that's from my data set, that's the title of the film

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:25.599
was, and then I can use those talking points like delta, trend, etc, to string together sentences.

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:32.160
So I've picked the trend terms higher and lower. And so I'll get some like Onward was 27 points

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:37.839
higher, Bonsters Inc was 17 points higher, Cars 2 was 17 points lower, just to describe the

00:17:37.839 --> 00:17:40.959
difference between the Metacritic and the Rotten Tomatoes and the Metacritic scores.

00:17:41.920 --> 00:17:48.560
I also can tell it to return columns as it does that. And I use this quite a bit to kind of bring

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:54.959
back the most interesting talking points. So I am able to say, yeah, bring back the delta and

00:17:54.959 --> 00:18:00.000
the raw delta, and then arrange it in descending order by just the absolute delta value. So when I

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:07.119
do that, the biggest change is, the biggest difference is with the movie Onward, followed

00:18:07.119 --> 00:18:12.560
by Monsters Inc and then Cars 2, but I can see both the absolute value and the raw delta,

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:17.119
showing that it's not only a big difference, it's a difference, positive, negative.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:26.719
So in practice, I just want to share some ways that I use this to create charts. So I use this

00:18:26.719 --> 00:18:33.839
in conjunction with the ggtext package. So again, I use the tidyverse downloads of a CRAN. And I

00:18:33.839 --> 00:18:38.160
just want to know which package had the biggest increase, what package had the lowest change

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:43.839
overall, and what package had the biggest decrease. So I was able to use that add headline

00:18:43.839 --> 00:18:50.640
column, saying, yeah, look at the package, tell me the trend, show it to me as a percentage. And

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:54.479
then I wanted it to nicely label, because the numbers were quite huge. These are in the millions.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:59.760
So in the skills package, there's this label number formatter, where I can say,

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:09.199
you know, give it accuracy, like into the tens unit. So it's like 2.1, 1.5. And then there's

